Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Jamaica. The Jamaican authorities have introduced a number of precautionary measures, including entry restrictions on all travelers from countries of concern, including the United Kingdom. If you are in Jamaica and need to leave, you are encouraged to make travel arrangements urgently before airlines end direct and indirect flights.
For information on how to return to the UK from Jamaica, see Return to the UK.
Those who entered Jamaica from countries of concern on or after 18 March, are required to self-quarantine for a total of 21 days from the date of arrival. Countries of concern listed by Jamaica include the UK, Canada, USA, China, Italy, South Korea, Iran, Singapore, Spain, France and Germany. All persons over the age of 75 must self-isolate at home until 9 April. No gatherings of more than 10 people in any one place is permitted.
Borders and travel
Only Jamaican citizens, spouses and children of Jamaican citizens, and permanent residents who left Jamaica before 20 March, will be permitted to enter the country. Travellers can expect disruption and termination of flights and should contact their airlines, travel agents and tour operators. Airline crew will be given special permission to enter the country but are expected to remain in specified locations with restricted movement.
All travellers who display any symptom of COVID-19, as per the case definition published by the Pan American Health Organization/World Health Organization, will be placed in immediate isolation at a health facility.
See additional advice on making travel plans to return to the UK, or what to do if you cannot depart immediately.
Medical facilities
Isolation facilities are operational at all public hospitals, with a specialist facility available at the National Chest Hospital. Quarantine facilities will be provided by the Government of Jamaica. For additional information check the Jamaican Ministry of Health website.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
